{"/service/ndnp/txdn/batch_txdn_evans_ver01/data/sn86063730/00332893774/1930102601/0459.xml":{"full_text":"CHINESE WAGE\nCHRISTIAN WAR\ngeneral Ordered to Attempt\nRelease of Priest Held\nFor Ransom\nHANKOW, China. Oct. 25\u2014GF)\u2014\nCommunists today carried their\nwarfare against foreign and native\nChristians into another province of\nChina.\nSweeping over Honan, the reds\nadded that piovince to the area\nof bandit destruction and mas\nsacre wrought in Kiangsi, Hupeh\nand Hunan provinces.\nSeveral American missionaries\nfled when cities of southern Honan\nwere plundered. Numerous Amer\nican priests were isolated at other\ntowns and their fate was unknown.\nThe Rev. Bert Nelson Minneap\nolis, captured by bandits at Kw\nangshan October 5, was held for\n$300.00h Mexican ransom 'about\n103,000 gold'. Whereabouts of Nel\naon. attached to the Lutheran Unit\ned Mission, was unknown Spurred\nby United States consulate requests\nfor action, the nationalist govern\nment ordered General Ho Ying\nChing at Chengchow to attempt\nhis release\nFather Thomas Megan. Amer\nican Catholic priest, arrived a*\nSinyang, after narrowlv escaping\ncapture when communists poured\ninto Loshan The city gates were\nreported opened by disgruntled and\nmutinous nationalist soldiers.\nDescribing his experiences. Me\ngan said he fled In the darkness\nas feds entered Loshan October 15\nHe luckily found a rope, scaled\nthe city wall, hid In a cemetery and\nafter dodging bands of communists\nthree days reached Sinyang.\nKwangshan also fell. Its gar\nrison was reported to have opened\nthe gates.\nMoving on to Kwangchow. thr\noutlaws besieged the city which\nhouses several Swiss Catholic\npriests and two German sisters.\nMuch concern !s felt in Hankow\nfor their welfa-e.\nThe reds attacked Sinyang but\nwere repulsed They captured the\nrailway station outside city walls\nburned railway material and man\u2019\nhouses. Departing with 100 person^\nheld for ransom, the outlaws spread\nterror through surrounding coun\nMARKETS\ni.- i\nCOTTON LIVELY\nNEW ORLEANS, Oct. 23\u2014y?H\nTrading was active in cotton tMay\nlor a short week-end session, and\nprices made new highs lor the\n'present upward movement at 10.10\nlor December, but most of this\ngain for the day was lost later on\nweek-end realizing.\nLiverpool came in decidedly bet\nter than due and as a result the\nmarket here opened 6 to 11 points\nup. Although there was a slight\nreaction soon axter the start on\nprofit taking the market soon rai\nded again on reported good specu\nlative and trade buying prices gain-\ning 18 to 21 points compared with\nthe previous close.\nNearly all of this gain was later\nlost on realizing for over the week\nend, but there was a moderate re\ncovery at the end and the close\nNvas steady at net gains for the\nday of 6 to 9 po.nts.\nThe census bureau reported tota1 i\nginnings to October 18 at 9.252.011\nrunning bales which was about j\nwhat the trade expected.\nLiverpool came In to 10 point*\nbetter than due and first trades\ngains here scarcely reflected a full\nresponse to the strength of the j\ncables. After a slight reaction of i\n6 to 6 points prices rallied on gcoti\ntrade buying and some speculative\nbuying and December traded up to j\n11.10, January to 11.23 and March t\nto 11.47 or 18 to 21 points above the\nprevious close.\nThe market eased off In the sec\nond hour on week-end realizing and\nlost a good part of the earlier ad\nvance but did not make new lows\nfor the day and the tone was steady\nat the end with December nosing\nat 11.00, January at 11.13 and Marcn\nat 11.35 or 6 to g points net higher\nlor the day on those active months\nPort receipts 52.690, for season\n4,076.221, last season 3,788 206. Ex\nports 14.774, for season 1,977.200,\nlast season 1.809.040. Port Stock I\n3,464.966, last year 2,211,466. Com-\nbinea shipboard stock at New Or-\nleans, Galveston and Houston 120,- j\n424. last year 191D75 Spot sales at i\nsouthern markets 44,709 last yea; j\n53,292.\nN NEW YORK COTTON\nNEW YORK. Oct. 25\u2014 TV- A\nContinuation of the recent buying, j\nwhich seemed to find encourage j\nment m restively steady rabies and\nunfavorable features in the weather\nnews. \u00abarr:\u00ab I prices into new high\nground for the present mverr.ent I\nin cotton here today.\nNew December sold up to 11 14\nor 20 points net higher and fullv\na cent a pound above the low level\ntouched earlier in the month, but\nofferings increased somewhat at\nthis figure, and there were re-\nnetiens of several points in the\nlater trading. December closed at\n11.03. with the general market j\nclosing barely steady at net ad-\nvances of 9 to 11 points.\nThe report of the census bureau j\nshowing 9.252.011 bales ginr. d prior\nto Octobc IS was closely in line\nwith recent private forecasts and\nwas not generally mentioned as r\nfactor In this morning's market\nOpinion was expressed in some\nquarters, that recent weather in\nthe south might have led to the\nabandonment of bearish expecta\ntions of a late reason increase ir\ncrop estimates, and accounted for\nsome of the current buying.\nLiverpool cables reported conti\nnental buying covering and trad\ncabling in that market and said\nthe demand for cotton cloth was\nbroadening with fair sales to China j\nand the near East.\n\nWHEAT DROPS\nCHICAGO. Oct. 25\u2014Fore\ncasts of a huge enlargement of\nwheat production this season in\nArgentina and Australia pulled\n-rain values downward today re\ngardless of Argentine reports of\nrust.\nf\nClosing quotations of wheat were\nweak at virtually the day's bottom\nleevl, 3-4 -1 3-8c a bushel lower\nthan yesterday s finish. Corn closed\n3-4-1 l-8c down, oats, 1-8 3-8c\nuff, and provisions varying from\n10c setback to a rise of 5c.\nExport business in North Amer\nican wheat today was again a dis\nappointment, and was described as\nconsisting of \u201cJust an occasional\nload.\"\nCorn and oats prices went lower\nwith wheat, notwithstanding that\ntoday's purchases of com here\navailable lor immediate use were\nthe largest in some time. The ma\njority of corn traders appeared\nreluctant to buy future deliveries\npending further evidence as to\nwhat to expect ffcout the size of\nthe coming movement of the corn\ncrop.\nProvisions averaged lower, re\nsponsive to downturns in quota\ntions on grain.\nClosing indemnities: wheat Dec\nember 77 5-8-3-4. 80 1-8 1-4;\nMarch 81 3-8. 84: May 82. 5-8. 85\n1-8. Corn December 76 1-8 -1-4. 78\n3-8; March bids 78; May 80 518\n3-4. 82 5-8.\nSTOC KS STEADY\nNEW YORK. Oct. 25\u2014 ^P, -Week\nend profit-taking was able to uak?\nonly minor indentations of stock\nprices today.\nThe market ragged after yester\nday's rally had been extended one\nto three points, but selling was\nlight and the net loss of TO leading\nissues was less than one fu\u2019l point,\ngales totaled 1.152.200 shares.\nFor the past few months Wall\nStreet has virtually ignored opti\nmistic statements on the business\noutlook, for it learned with some\nchagrin just how premature proph\necies can be. However, the lact\nthe depression has run for so long\naligns the time element on the side\nof a turn, and hence the views ol\nthe steel executives and others or\nhe prospects for improvement\nfound readier listeners.\nTwo or three weak spots devel\noped in the stock list. J. I. Case\nbroke 13 points to a new low ol\nrumors of new financing and at tb*\nday's minimum of 115N was selling\nat the lowest price in four years\nRecovery was fractional, interna\ntional Harvester dropped 3 points\nand Montgomery Ward lost a\npoint to 19 also a new low.\nAfter an irregularly mgher\nopening, the market ran alofig or\na higher scale throughout the first\nfour. U. S. Steel touch 152i, up\nnearly 2 points, and there were\nrallies of a point in America Can\nDu Pont. American Water Works\nfConsolidated Gas. Atchison. Erie,\nNew York Central and others.\nIt seemed too much to expect\nhowever, that the market could\nclose higher on two successive\ndays, especially in v\u2018ew of Friday\u2019s\nbroad advance, and profit-taking\nreduced or eliminated most of the\ngains, while many w^rs converted\niruo small losse Wescinghous0,\nwhich had opened 3 points higher\non a 10,000 share block, dipped be\nlow the previous close but managed\nto finish up. U. E. Steel held\nof a point of its advance, but\nAmerican Can, Standard Oil of\nNew Jersey. Radio General Elec\ntric and Gtneral Motors were off\nfractionally. American Telephone,\nInternational Telephone, Union\nPacific, Johns-Manville and Gil\nlette lost 1 to 2 net. Allied Chem\nical anu Eastman Kodak yieldeu 3\npoints.\nChanges in foreign exchanges\nwere small. Continental rates\nruled steady. The Spanish peseta\nadvanced.\nK. C. LIVESTOCK\nKANSAS CITY. Oct. 25\u2014<AV-<U.\n3. Department of Agriculture)\nLivestock trade around the eleven\nnarket circuit this week was fea\nured by fluctuation in prices.\n[Tattle broke sharply early in the\nvefk, but later moderate activity\nieveloped on beef steers and year\nmgs and several centers are clos\nng with a moderate advance.\nChicago scored 13 50 on choice\nearhng steers and realized 12.50\n3n finished heavy steers. Stocker\nmd feeder classes were on a steady\no 25 lower basis with country de\nnend fairly broad. Aggregate re\neipts were estimated at 305,50 as\n\u25a0ompared with 272 804 las week\nmd 330,158 the corresponding pe\niod a year ago.\nHogs were sharply lower the fore\n\u2019art of the week, but there was a\neaction later with part of the early\niechne recovered. Current quota\nions are unevenly steady to 50\nower as compared with a week\nigo.\nKEEP THIS AD\nfor it\nand\n$3.50\nentitles\nyou to\ninit gurgrt\u00abu% nvujwiKia rri\nsonalitv Pfrmanfnt Wave\nA regular $15\nwave for only\nThis wave mar be (ftven with\ncroquiirnHe machine if desir\ned. Each wave known for its\nindividuality. All hair scien\ntifrally tested before wavinf.\nEvery operator an artist. You\nare assured of a soft natural\ncurl with\nSATISFACTION\nGUARANTEED\nFor Appointment\nPhone 841\nHollywood Beauty\nShoppe\n116 S. First St.f Harlingen\nI... 1,1\nI Valley Society1\nTelephone 7 J\nDINNER PARTY HONORS\nMISS GARRETT\nMiss Beth Garrett was named\nhonoree at a surprise birthday din\nner party, one evening recently,\nat the home of Mrs. H. E. Sugg.\nA white birthday cake, with pink\ncandles, made an attractive center\npiece for the table, surrounded by\npink corona blossoms.\nPlaces were marked for Miss\nGarrett, Miss Ruth Fink. Miss\nGeorgia de Vries, Miss Mary Ann\nMakens. Mrs. J. L. Johnson and\nthe hostess.\n\nMRS. BUCKINGHAM\nBRIDGE HONOREE\nMrs. J. C. Bauer was hostess at\ni a pretty courtsey one afternoon\nduring the past week, naming a;\nguest of honor. Mrs. Nell Buck\ningham of Weslaco.\nThe afternoon was spent in play\ning bridge with Mrs. Linton Acker\nmaking high score and also cut\nting the cards high. Mrs. Bucking\nham received a lovely guest prize\nOthers making up the personnel\nfor the afternoon were Mrs. Louis\nSchmidt, Mrs. Jack Hawkins. Mrs\nC. W. Robinson. Mrs. W. Y. Robin\nson and Miss Bettie Ammons.\n\nMEMBERS MEET AT\nLAWSON HOME\nThe members of the Worthwhile\nclub held their meeting this week\nat the home of Mrs. C. J. Lawson\nMrs. A. W. Arnett presided at\nthe business meeting. A social hour\nfollowed during which the hostess\nserved a refreshment course.\n\nVALLEY CLCB\nORGANIZED\nThe Rio Grande Valley club of\nOur Lady of the Lake College af\nSan Antonio has recently been or\nganized, according to Miss Beatrice\nI Pierce of this city, a student at\nthat institution, and w\u2019ho has been\nelected president of the freshman\nclass.\n\nMISS WIGGINS MAJOR\nOF FISH\u201d SCHOOL\nMiss Marjorie Wiggins of thi'\ncity, a student at the College of\nIndustrial Arts at Denton, Texas\nwhere she is a physical education\nmajor, is one of the 28 majors to\nconduct \u201cfish'\u2019 schools.\n\u201cFish\u201d schools are organized tc\nacquaint the freshman and new\nstudents with the songs, history\nand tradition cf their alma mater\nAt the close of the instruction pe\nriod. each freshman is awarded r\ndiploma by her dean, showing tha/\nshe has successfully completed the\nwo-k outlined in the \u201cfish\u201d school\ncurriculum.\n\n\u2022MEXICAN LUNCHEON,\nBRIDGE HOSTESS\nThe Silk Stocking club held r\nmost enjoyable meeting on Wed\nnesday with Mrs. E. E. Johnson\nhostess at a Mexican style lunch\neon, at her home on Ohio avenue.\nAfter luncheon contract bridge\nwas played with Mrs. Roy Tolson\nscoring high in the games.\n\nPRETTY HALLOWE'EN\nMOTIFS FEATURED\nMrs. Jack Hawkins was hostess\nat a pretty bridge party on Wed\nnesday afternoon at her home on\nSouth Ohio Avenue. Carrying out\nthe Hallowe en theme in floral dec\norations and table outfittings.\nYellow cosmos tverr ut?d with\npleasing effect. In the games of j\nbridge Mr.s. W. Y. Robinson scored 1\n\nhigh and Mrs. C. W. Robinson scor\ned second high.\nA two course refreshment plate\nfollowed the games. Covers were\nplaced for Mesdames Linton Acker.\nC. F. Archer, W. Y. Robinson, James\nLaGro of Brownsville and Abe Axel\nrod of Harlingen.\n\nPRETTY COLOR SCHEME\nBRIDGE EVENT FEATURE\nMrs. Ralph Love was hostess tr\nthe Wednesday afternoon Bridge\nclub at her home west of the city\nwith four tables of players present.\nA color scheme of yellow pre\nvailed in the rooms, where baskets\nbowls and vases of yellow cosmos\nwere arranged at vantage points.\nThe lovely score trophies were\ndone in yellow and the. tempting\nrefreshment plate showed the same\ncolor note.\nMrs. James Howze scored high\nin the games and Mrs. G. C. Fitt?\nscored for consolat'on. Guests of\nthe club on this afternoon were\nMrs. A. D. Newkirk. Miss Dorothy\nWarner of Chicago, and Miss Eliz\nabeth Lorenz of Benton Harbor\nMichigan.\n\nCOTERIE BRIDGE\nCLUB MEETS\nMrs. Henry Menton entertained\nthe Coterie Bridge club on Wed\nnesday afternoon, using roses of\nmany colors for floral adornment\nFour tables of players were pres\nent for the games of auction bridge,\nwith Mrs. Henry Lauderdale scor\ning high. Mrs. Kathryn Chadlck\nwas high among the guer\u20183. thr\nother two guests being Mrs. Thom\nas Shock of La Feria. and Mrs. H\nV. Leist of Sedalia. Missouri.\n\nANNUAL RALLY\nDAY HELD\nA large number of women were\npresent at the annual Rally Day\nprogram of the Presbyterian Wo\nir.ens Auxiliary held thts week at\nthe church, with Mrs. J. N. Pace\npresident, presiding.\nMrs. Kathryn Chadick had charge\nof the devotional, her subject being\n\u2018Glad Tidings of Good Things.\u201d\nMrs. H E. Bennett led the dis\ncussion of the program, the theme\nbeing \u201cJapans Evangelistic Move\nment Under the Leadership of Ka\ng;.wa, A Noted Japanese Minister.\"\nThose having parts on the program\nwere Mrs. E. B Witmer. Mrs. Wal\nter Swarner and Mrs. Bennett.\n\nAUXILIARY VISITS\nNEWCOMERS\n\u201cCalling Day\u201d was observed this\nweek in the Womens Auxiliary of\nthe Christian church, their regular\nmeeting being dispensed with.\nNew residents of the cltv and\nsurrounding community were vis\nited.\n\nBAPTIST AUXILIARY\nThe Baptist Auxiliary met with\nMrs. S. C. Bates.\nMrs. John Briscoe had charge of\nthe Royal Servioe study obi the\n\"Work of the States in the South\nern Baptist Convention.\u201d\n\nSTUDIES CONTINUED\nThe Methodist Auxiliary met at\nthe church for the second of a ser\nies of studies being conducted by\nMrs. H. L. Schmalzried.\nMrs. H. T. Tidmore and Mrs. Geo.\nPotts assisted with the study of the\nafternoon.\n\nPERSONALS\nMr. and Mrs, Emmett Lacklev of\nWichita Falls have arrived in the\nValley to make their home. They\nare situated here in South Palm\nGardens.\nMrs. Fleet Lentz was a guest this\nweek in the home of Mrs. W. O.\nBrown in San Benito.\nMr. and Mrs. J. R. Barry ha\\e\nreturned from an overland trip to\nAt Insist\nYour On\nNearest W Velvet\nGrocer 1 F|\\J Butter\nTTjersey\nButter\nThe Better Butter\n\u201cThe following merchants are boosters of the\nVelvet Jersey Butter; if your grocer is not in\ncluded in the list, ask him to supply you with the\nbutter that is made to stand every test.\nHARMS G E N\nDavis Tourist Camp\nMcLenson's Grocery\nJitney Jungle\nRa\u00bb*er's Grocery\nGriffin's I. G. A.\nSouthern's I. G. A.\nHofo\u2019s Grocery\nD. B. Kline\nBROWNSVILLE:\nTourist Auto Supply Co.\nWellers Service Station\nJ. A. Champion\nJitney Jungle\nAimworth Collin Self Serv.\nAinsworth Colgrtn\nCentral Cash Grocery\nCity Market\nThese stores are noted for their stocks of ex\ntra quality foods. Naturally they would choose\nVelvet Jersey Butter, because\n\u201cthe quality is guaranteed\nlhe Da\u2019ry Products Co.\nKingsville Alice\nUJ' m i 1\nI\nFort Worth and Dallas where the\natt\"nded the state fair.\nMr. and Mrs. Paul Ruckell had as\nguests this week, Herbert Baker, of\nAkron, Ohio. Mr. Baker is in the\nValley visiting his sister, Mrs. N. J.\nKendrick of San Benito.\nMrs. J. D. South of Corpus Chris\nti, was a guest here this week in\nthe home of Mrs. H. K. Feather\nstone. Mrs. South was formerly\nMrs. R. J. Drysdale of this city.\nShe was married to Mr. South two\nweeks ago.\nMrs. F. H. Redmond of San An\nI tomo, was a guest here this week of\nMrs. Paul Ruckell. Mrs. Redmond\nwas in the Valley as a delegate to\nthe Methodist conference which was\nheld at Harlingen.\nMr. and Mrs. Harry Williams and\ndaughter. Shirley, have returned to\ntheir home in Grand Rapids, Mich\nalter a visit here in the home of\nMi. Williams\u2019 sister, Mrs. Florence\nKalbfleisch.\nMr. and Mrs. J. B. Spruce of\nFioresvtllc are guests here in the\nhome of Rev. and Mrs. M. H Keen.\nI They are Mrs. Keen\u2019s parents.\nOwen Stone, secretary of the\nLlano Grande country club has just\nreturned from Tampico. Mexico.\nI where he visited his brother, R. W.\nStone.\nMrs. G. E Huff and children have\nreturned from a visit to relatives in\nArizona.\nMr. and Mrs. W. L. Yarbrough\nhave returned to their home in Dal\nlas after a visit here in the home\nof Mr. and Mrs. George Markham.\nRev. C. P. Owen, pastor of the\nlocal Presbyterian church, has re\nturned from Big Springs, where he\nettended the Presbyteriai state sy\nnod. WThile there. Mr Owen was\ncalled to Bonham, a former pas\ntorate, to conduct a funeral. Mr.\nCwen has a brother, R. L. Owen. In\nBig Springs, pastor of the Presby\nterian church there.\nMr. and Mrs. Lynn Calvin, for\nmerly of Walcott, N. Y.. have mov\ned to the Valley and have purchased\nproperty.\nALL THERE\nFirst Picnicker: Isn't this an idea!\nspot for a picnic dinner?\nSecond Ditto: It must be. Fifty\nmillion insects can't possibly have\nmade a mistake.\u2014Toronto Globe.\nNASH\ntsftpearanct and cohort art netablj advanced\n5^erftrmanct it tmtether, mart thrilling than ever\nfrom *795to *2.025\nr. o. b. factoriis\nLowest Priced\nSix in All\nNash History\nThe 6~6o Serits\n*795 t0 *845\nIVorhT 3 Lowest\nPriced Eight,\n4-Door Sedan\nThe 8-70 Series\n$945 to $995\nOnly Twin\nIgnition Eight\nat Its Price\nThe 8-80 Serin\n*I245/0*!375\nFinest Eight\nMotoring\nMoney Can Buy\nThe 8-90 Serus\n1565 to%2025\nThe four new cars presented by Nash are deliberately\ndesigned and built to give the public more motor car for\nits money than any manufacturer has ever offered before.\nThe actual increase in dollar value is from $200 in the\n1 lower priced models to $400 in the higher priced series.\nA NEW DEAL FOR TODAY\u2019S DOLLAR\nArcher-Deyo Nash Co.\nMERCEDES, TEXAS\nAt the Borderland\nNow, more than ever, the living room will be\nthe center of home activity. Cool weather\nmakes evenings more enjoyable at home. The\nholidays will soon be here\u2014parties, guests, etc.\nYou will enjoy your home more if your living\nroom is properly furnished. One of our new\nliving room suits will work wonders. Never\n1 have we had such a large assortment of stylish\nI popular priced suits.\nI Here is the very suite that you have always\nwanted. A tapestry covered suite at a mod\nerate price. Never have we been able to offer\nsuch a handsome suite at such a low price.\nSpring construction throughout, reversible\ncushions- *4\nEnjoy Your\nFurniture\nWhile You Pay\nAny Suite Delivered\nFor Small Down\nPayment\nBalance on Easy\nv Terms\nSpecial Value\nOccasional Chair\n$9.95\nCombination tapestry and velour\nupholstery. Hardwood walnut fin\nish. Delivered for 95c down\u2014Bal\nance weekly.\n2 pieces $98J\u00a3\nas illustrated above left\nP rt\n3 Piec<\n(Jverstuired Suite\n-Vv\nas illustrated\nThis stylish new suite has the serpentine fronts with deep spring\nseats and Nachman spring filled cushions. All cushions have rever\nsible covers. The entire suite is upholstered in a combination of\nmulti-colored velours. The suite consists of davenport, club chair\nand button back chair.\n\n3-Piece Jacquard Velour Covered Suite. Each piece is covered\nwith an extra high grade Jacquard velour. The cushions have\nreversible covers.\nThere are dozens of new Living Room Suites in our store\nto select from. New and different coverings. Prices that will\nplease your purse. Styles that will please your t*\u00bbste.","height":"37020","width":"27788"}}
